<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-415-812  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 415 812.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  July 2 1990 v1 n6 p22(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Copyright violators: Paperback Software International andamp; StephensonSoftware Ltd. ruled violators of Lotus 1-2-3 copyright. Keystrokefor keystroke admitted. (court rules in favor of Lotus DevelopmentCorp.)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Cases)Paperback Software International (Cases)Stephenson Software (Cases).andO;Ticker:    LOTS.andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 (Spreadsheet software) (Cases).andO;Topic:     CopyrightLaw SuitLegal IssuesSpreadsheetsSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The United States District Court in Boston ruled that Paperback SoftwareInternational and Stephenson Software Ltd. infringed Lotus DevelopmentCorp.'s copyright in Lotus 1-2-3 by selling their software program,VP-Planner, Lotus announced Thursday.andM;Federal Judge Robert E. Keeton held that Paperback and Stephenson copied theLotus 1-2-3 user interface, which is protected by Federal copyright law.andM;In the opinion issued, Federal Judge Robert E. Keeton ruled, &quot;The userinterface of 1-2-3 is its most unique element, and is the aspect that hasmade 1-2-3 so popular.andP;  That defendants went to such trouble to copy thatelement is a testament to its substantiality...I determine thatcopyrightability of the user interface of 1-2-3 is established.andM;&quot;Not only is the copying in this case so 'overwhelming and pervasive' as topreclude, as a matter of law, any assertion of independent creation ...andP;  butalso, defendants in this case have admitted that they copied these elementsof protected expression,&quot; Keeton added.andM;Lotus filed suit against Paperback and Mosaic Software Inc. in January 1987,charging the defendants deliberately copied, keystroke for keystroke, thespreadsheet module of Lotus 1-2-3, the company's best-selling spreadsheetsoftware.andP;  The case was tried in February and March 1990 in United StatesFederal District Court in Boston.andM;&quot;Today's decision is a victory not only for Lotus, but for the softwareindustry as a whole,&quot; said Tom Lemberg, Lotus's vice president and generalcounsel.andP;  &quot;The Court's ruling reaffirms Congress's intent to protect softwareinnovators from imitators.andP;  This is good news for developers who, withoutprotection, might find it unfeasible to market their creations and forcustomers who depend on new technology to advance the effectiveness of theirbusinesses.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>